MIDDLEWARE NOTES

PURPOSE:
Middleware acts as a Security Guard.

It runs BEFORE a page loads and decides:
- Allow access
- Redirect user

------------------------------------------------

WHY DO WE NEED IT?

Without middleware:

Not Logged In User
        ↓
Can try opening:
/dashboard

Logged In User
        ↓
Can still open:
/sign-in
/sign-up

This creates bad user experience and security issues.

------------------------------------------------

REQUEST FLOW

Browser
   ↓
Middleware
   ↓
Page

Middleware always runs before the page.

------------------------------------------------

JWT CONNECTION

User Login
    ↓
JWT stored in browser cookie
    ↓
Middleware reads JWT
    ↓
Decides whether user is authenticated

------------------------------------------------

getToken()

const token = await getToken({ req })

Purpose:
Read JWT from browser cookie.

Logged In User:
token = {
  _id,
  username,
  ...
}

Not Logged In:
token = null

MEMORY:
getToken() = "Am I logged in?"

------------------------------------------------

matcher

Tells Next.js where middleware should run.

Example:

matcher = [
  '/',
  '/sign-in',
  '/sign-up',
  '/verify/:path*',
  '/dashboard/:path*'
]

Middleware runs only on these routes.

------------------------------------------------

RULE 1

If token exists
(User is logged in)

and user tries to visit:

/sign-in
/sign-up
/
/verify

Redirect to:

/dashboard

Reason:
Logged in users don't need auth pages.

FLOW:

Logged In
    ↓
Open /sign-in
    ↓
Redirect /dashboard

------------------------------------------------

RULE 2

If token does NOT exist

and user tries:

/dashboard

Redirect to:

/sign-in

Reason:
Unauthenticated users cannot access dashboard.

FLOW:

Not Logged In
      ↓
Open /dashboard
      ↓
Redirect /sign-in

------------------------------------------------

NextResponse.redirect()

Used to send user to another page.

Example:

redirect('/sign-in')

------------------------------------------------

NextResponse.next()

Means:

Everything is okay.
Continue loading page.

------------------------------------------------

WHY NOT useSession()?

Middleware runs on Server/Edge before React loads.

useSession() only works inside React components.

Therefore middleware uses:

getToken()

instead of

useSession()

------------------------------------------------

IS MIDDLEWARE REQUIRED?

NO.

You can protect pages manually:

const session = await getServerSession()

if (!session) {
  redirect('/sign-in')
}

But you'll repeat this on every protected page.

Middleware lets you:

Write once
Protect many routes

------------------------------------------------

MEMORY TRICK

JWT = ID Card

getToken()
      ↓
Read ID Card

Middleware
      ↓
Security Guard

No Token?
      ↓
No Dashboard

Has Token?
      ↓
No Sign-In Page

Otherwise
      ↓
Allow Access

------------------------------------------------

ONE-LINE SUMMARY

Middleware is a security guard that runs before pages load, reads the JWT using getToken(), and redirects users based on whether they are authenticated.



